data.content:
Replace `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>`, which lets you inspect the exception and pinpoints exactly which line threw:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();

    var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(
        () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));

    Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName); // bonus: verify details
}
```

**Why:**
- `[ExpectedException]` passes even if the *wrong line* throws — `Assert.ThrowsExactly` scopes the check to the exact lambda.
- You get the exception back, so you can assert on `ParamName`, `Message`, etc.
- Use `Assert.Throws<T>` if you want to match derived exception types too; `ThrowsExactly<T>` matches only the exact type.
